\title{closure of [bijections](jms-00KR) under [identity](jms-00II) and [composition](jms-00IN)}
\date{2024-01-23}
\author{jonmsterling}
\contributor{marcelofiore}
\taxon{theorem}
\import{jms-00JB}

\p{The [identity function](jms-00KI) is a [bijection](jms-00KR), and the [composition](jms-00IN) of [bijections](jms-00KR) yields a [bijection](jms-00KR).}

\proof{
 \p{The inverse to the [identity function](jms-00KI) #{\idn{A}\colon A\to A} is simply itself.}
 \p{Fix [bijections](jms-00KR) #{f\colon A\to B} and #{g\colon B\to C}, so that we have [inverses](jms-00KR) #{f\inv\colon B\to A} and #{g\inv\colon C\to B}. The [inverse](jms-00KR) to the [composite function](jms-00KI) #{g\circ f\colon A \to C} is the [composite](jms-00KI) #{f\inv\circ g\inv\colon C \to A}. The [section/retraction](jms-00KS) conditions follow by those for #{f} and #{g} using the [associative and unit laws of composition](jms-00IP).}
}